nverge to affect flood control in Winnipeg. She questions technicalities produced and maintained in tandem with settler folkways at the expense of the plural legal cultures of Indigenous nations. The dynamics of this experimental ethnography feel familiar yet strange: here, many of the starring actors are not human. Ice and water – materializing as bodies, elements, and digital signals – act with diatoms, diversions, sensors, sandbags, and satellites, looping theories about glacial erratics and feminist science studies into scenes from neighbourhood parks, conferences, survey maps, plays, archival photos, a novel, an emergency press conference, LiDAR images, and a lab experiment in a bathtub. Through storytelling and environmental analytics, Just One Rain Away provides a starting point for cross-cultural discussions about how expert knowledge and practice should inform egalitarian decision-making about flood control and, more broadly, decolonize current ways of thinking, being, and becoming with rivers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFlood controlxSocial aspectszManitobazWinnipeg. 0aFlood controlzManitobazWinnipegxDecision making. 0aFlood controlzManitobazWinnipeg. 0aFloodszManitobazWinnipeg. 0aRiversxSocial aspectszManitobazWinnipeg. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aAgassiz.  aAnthropocene.  aArt.  aAssiniboine River.  aCentrePort.  aEnvironment.  aHoller.  aHoop.  aIndigenous.  aLake.  aLiDAR.  aManitoba.  aPortage Diversion.  aRed River.  aSt Martin.  aThe Forks.  aWinnipeg.  aartifice.  aavulsion.  abreach.  achronotope.  aclimate crisis.  acontrolled.  acultures.  adecolonization.  adiatoms.  aengineering.  aerratics.  afocal point.  aforecasts.  ageoscience.  agovernance.  ahabitus.  ahydrological balance. 